WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
Hello, my name is George Stagg, and I'm the lead developer of webR.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:17.080
So today, I want to talk about what I think is particularly magical about some of the

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:19.200
things that webR can do.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:23.040
Before I start, I do want to say the first piece of magic is this wonderful logo, which

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.200
I didn't design.

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:29.559
I gave Dawley the hex logo for webR and the description of this talk, and this is what

00:00:29.559 --> 00:00:30.559
it came up with.

00:00:30.559 --> 00:00:32.680
And if that's not magic, I don't know what is.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:36.240
That is just incredible.

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:41.799
So as hopefully you picked up from Joe's talk, webR is a system that allows you to execute

00:00:41.799 --> 00:00:46.720
R code directly in a web browser without a supporting R server.

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:49.080
But webR can do more than this.

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:54.119
It's not just about adding text R code into a box and then getting text output out of

00:00:54.119 --> 00:00:55.119
a box.

00:00:55.520 --> 00:01:00.279
WebR lets you interact with the running R session in a very particular way, and it allows

00:01:00.279 --> 00:01:05.199
you to manipulate the R environment and reach in there and tweak things.

00:01:05.199 --> 00:01:07.320
It's this kind of stuff I want to talk about today.

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:11.599
This is the kind of thing that I find particularly magical.

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:15.400
When I showed this for the first time in a meeting, the response I got from the others

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:18.120
in the meeting was just mind-blown.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:22.839
So I thought, well, there's no chance I can't share something that good with posit.conf.

00:01:22.839 --> 00:01:23.839
I have to.

00:01:23.839 --> 00:01:30.080
So the way this all works is WebAssembly.

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:34.800
The technical fancy way of saying what it is is a portable binary format, and it's designed

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:37.160
so that it can run anywhere.

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:42.239
In particular, this is in browsers, but it can also run server-side.

00:01:42.239 --> 00:01:46.919
And what I mean by that, for those who are interested, you can run webR in places like

00:01:46.919 --> 00:01:53.599
the cloud and server-side and edge nodes and anywhere where there's a WebAssembly engine.

00:01:53.639 --> 00:01:57.680
In the future, WebR will be able to run better in those than currently, but certainly the

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:02.480
support is there through WebAssembly for those kind of computing environments.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:06.559
So WebR is a version of the R interpreter built for WebAssembly, and that's what allows

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:10.199
you to run that R code, as Joe explained.

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:11.199
So why WebR?

00:02:11.199 --> 00:02:13.160
Why would you be interested in WebR?

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:17.639
In addition to all the shiny live stuff, which is going to be a great boon to education,

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:20.160
there are already other tools that can do similar things.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:25.600
This is a quota extension by James Balamuta that can actually inject runnable code blocks

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:28.080
directly into a quota output.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:33.759
This is going to be amazing for educational material or even package documentation.

00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:37.080
Imagine going to a website, a Pakistan website, and being able to play with a package without

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:39.080
having to install it.

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:43.320
In certain situations where the network is locked down and that package may not even

00:02:43.320 --> 00:02:45.839
be available to install.

00:02:45.839 --> 00:02:50.080
We saw interactive presentations, and as Joe mentioned, there are people currently

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:56.919
looking into running portable R applications and reproducibility by using shiny live.

00:02:56.919 --> 00:03:02.199
This works because WebAssembly provides very strong security features and reproducibility

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:08.660
features that aren't provided by a normal CPU architecture.

00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:11.399
So today I'm going to show off some WebR magic.

00:03:11.399 --> 00:03:13.679
I'll explain why I think it's useful.

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:18.440
I'll explain a little bit about how it works, depending on the time, and I will be using

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:20.320
JavaScript.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:23.000
Probably by the end of this, there will be quite a few people who say, gosh, I'm glad

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.919
I don't have to use JavaScript.

00:03:24.919 --> 00:03:28.279
But don't worry, I'm not going to assume any particular knowledge, and I don't want you

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:30.839
to think too much about the syntax of the code.

00:03:30.839 --> 00:03:36.360
I want you to think more about what the code is doing to an R environment.

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:37.360
So let's start.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:38.880
I call this magic trick mind reading.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:42.639
So on the left-hand side of the screen there is an R session, and on the right-hand side

00:03:42.639 --> 00:03:46.080
of the screen is a linked JavaScript session.

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:52.119
And right at the top, in the top left-hand corner, I've set a value in R equal to 1729,

00:03:52.119 --> 00:03:56.839
and then in JavaScript, I've run a piece of code that's going to reach into that R environment

00:03:56.839 --> 00:04:00.800
that's currently running and pull out the value of that variable.

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:06.759
And you can see straightaway that it's returned the word promise, which is not great, but

00:04:06.759 --> 00:04:08.160
it's how it works.

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:12.279
JavaScript's way of dealing with asynchronous programming is through this promises paradigm,

00:04:12.279 --> 00:04:16.160
but luckily there's a keyword so that if you put the word await before what you want

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:21.399
to do, JavaScript will wait for the result to come back, wait for that promise to resolve,

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:24.519
and just give you what the result is.

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:28.959
What you get back is a WebR object that looks kind of strange, it's got this sort of proxy

00:04:28.959 --> 00:04:33.519
word on it, but what you can think of that as is basically like a black box that's linked

00:04:33.519 --> 00:04:35.480
to a certain R object.

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:40.040
So what's happened here is that little API call for WebR has reached into the environment

00:04:40.079 --> 00:04:43.920
and grabbed that foo object and returned a reference to it.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:45.359
And from that, you can do work on it.

00:04:45.359 --> 00:04:50.000
There's a whole set of WebR APIs that allows you to run methods on these R objects, and

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.880
in this case, the method I've used is a method to JS, and that's taking that object and converting

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:56.880
it into a JavaScript object.

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:01.040
So you can see the value of that object shown on the screen there is 1729.

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:05.480
And when you think about it, this is actually quite special, because if you were just working

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:11.359
with strings, you'd have to take that number back from the standard output of a normal

00:05:11.359 --> 00:05:12.359
R program.

00:05:12.359 --> 00:05:16.000
Well, it would be even worse if you had something like a vector, okay?

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.959
If you had something like a vector, you'd then have to take your string, you'd have

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:23.119
to split it on commas, you'd have to get rid of all the white space, you'd have to parse

00:05:23.119 --> 00:05:24.119
all the values.

00:05:24.119 --> 00:05:28.059
It's a whole micro to get those values out of R if you're working with putting strings

00:05:28.059 --> 00:05:29.600
in and getting strings out.

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:34.079
But here, you just get the numbers directly from WebAssembly's memory in a format that

00:05:34.079 --> 00:05:39.359
JavaScript understands and in a format that JavaScript can use.

00:05:39.359 --> 00:05:42.239
The next example I'm going to call conjuring variables.

00:05:42.239 --> 00:05:45.920
So here, there's an example where in the R session, there's an object foo, but it doesn't

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:46.920
exist.

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:47.920
It's not there.

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:49.600
The environment is empty.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:58.440
Here you can see that we run a piece of code that puts a vector of JavaScript values into

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:04.160
R's memory, and then associates that with an object in that environment.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:08.959
So what I've done is I've created a new object and given it a name.

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:12.119
And then, when you type the name in, the object appears.

00:06:12.119 --> 00:06:15.239
It appears out of nowhere, like I've pulled it out of a hat.

00:06:15.239 --> 00:06:19.239
I think this is awesome, because there's only a few situations I can think of where that

00:06:19.239 --> 00:06:22.200
kind of thing can happen, where you can have an object that's not there, and then all of

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:23.200
a sudden it's there.

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:24.200
So I think that's great.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:25.200
But it's not the best trick.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:26.679
The best trick's coming up.

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:27.679
This is my favorite thing.

00:06:27.679 --> 00:06:28.679
Well, OK.

00:06:28.679 --> 00:06:30.359
A little bit early.

00:06:30.359 --> 00:06:32.640
You can also do a complex JavaScript object.

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:36.279
So you can see here on the right-hand side of the screen, this is a nested JavaScript

00:06:36.279 --> 00:06:41.320
object, which is recursively, automatically converted into a nested R list.

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:42.320
OK, here.

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:43.839
I got excited for this.

00:06:43.839 --> 00:06:45.920
So imagine you've got an R function.

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:50.200
Here I'm just creating some random normal numbers.

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:51.200
It's scaled.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:52.200
It doesn't really matter what the function is.

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:57.119
The point is that you can put some arguments in, and you get some numbers back.

00:06:57.119 --> 00:06:58.480
We're going to do the same trick we did before.

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:01.279
We're going to get a reference to that function object.

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:02.779
We're not running the function.

00:07:02.779 --> 00:07:07.519
We're grabbing a reference to that actual function that lives in R's memory.

00:07:07.519 --> 00:07:10.359
And you can see you've got another one of these strange proxy objects that you can work

00:07:10.359 --> 00:07:11.359
with.

00:07:11.359 --> 00:07:12.359
But this is really cool.

00:07:12.359 --> 00:07:16.640
You can invoke it, just like a normal JavaScript function.

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:21.239
Those arguments are automatically converted into R objects, and the result is automatically

00:07:21.239 --> 00:07:24.079
converted back into JavaScript.

00:07:24.079 --> 00:07:28.799
This to me is really magical, because you don't even have to know that that's an R function.

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:34.760
As far as you're concerned, it's just a JavaScript function that returns a promise.

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:39.119
That means you can use it with native JavaScript frameworks that are just assuming that you're

00:07:39.119 --> 00:07:42.519
going to give it a JavaScript function for something like a callback.

00:07:42.519 --> 00:07:44.940
It doesn't need to know how to work with WebR.

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:49.440
You just give it a function, and it invokes it.

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:53.559
So these examples, they're relatively simple, right?

00:07:53.559 --> 00:07:57.760
But they do demonstrate something which I think could be a new and useful workflow when

00:07:57.760 --> 00:07:59.359
using WebR.

00:07:59.359 --> 00:08:03.519
The three examples are about moving data into the R environment, getting data out of the

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:07.239
R environment, and, of course, running R functions.

00:08:07.239 --> 00:08:10.420
Now moving data into the R environment, that could be something more complicated.

00:08:10.420 --> 00:08:12.200
You could be doing a database connection.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:15.920
You could be doing a user data upload of something like a CSV.

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:17.820
You could be getting data from a REST API.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:23.119
These are things that the browser can do inside JavaScript.

00:08:23.119 --> 00:08:26.359
One-side WASM, but you can do it in JavaScript.

00:08:26.359 --> 00:08:31.399
Running R functions, I just ran a small function there that generated some random numbers.

00:08:31.399 --> 00:08:36.080
But imagine, this could be some kind of complex data manipulation using dplyr.

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:41.119
It could be a really sophisticated modeling pipeline with something like tidy models.

00:08:41.119 --> 00:08:44.719
And getting that data back into JavaScript, that means you don't have to live in the R

00:08:44.719 --> 00:08:46.440
world if you don't want to.

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:50.239
You could take that data from WebR, create a dashboard in JavaScript.

00:08:50.239 --> 00:08:51.960
You could offer it as a file download.

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:56.039
You could even use interactive visualizations in completely different frameworks, such as

00:08:56.039 --> 00:08:58.400
D3 or Observable.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:02.000
And this isn't even that complicated.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.799
That amount of code is enough to take WebR and integrate it with Observable.js.

00:09:06.799 --> 00:09:13.440
And this visualization here is a web-native observable plot, but the data has been taken

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:15.919
and computed from WebR.

00:09:15.919 --> 00:09:21.000
And I think that is one of the best things about WebR, the fact that it can integrate

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:26.880
so well into pre-existing frameworks that already exist for data visualization and data

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:29.119
science on the web.

00:09:29.119 --> 00:09:31.000
Okay.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.479
So how does this work?

00:09:33.479 --> 00:09:38.000
So the RWASM process runs inside something called a JavaScript web worker.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.359
This is important because if it didn't do that, it meant that every time you asked R

00:09:41.359 --> 00:09:44.640
to do something, your entire browser would freeze.

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:48.760
And it's not a good user experience, to say the least.

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:52.119
That allows the main thread to remain responsive.

00:09:52.119 --> 00:09:56.840
And so to make this work, communication between that main browser thread, where your website

00:09:56.840 --> 00:10:01.280
is and where you're interacting with things and pressing buttons, and the R process is

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:02.679
handled by message passing.

00:10:02.679 --> 00:10:09.080
So input messages go to R, output messages come back to you on the main thread.

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:17.239
So if you're working with code, you could imagine you give WebR the command Rnome, and

00:10:17.239 --> 00:10:21.239
the worker thread thinks for a bit, the main thread remains responsive, and then after

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:22.799
a while, you get some output back.

00:10:22.799 --> 00:10:26.280
And you can see here's an example of what I meant before about this kind of thing being

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:27.640
difficult to work with.

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:28.719
You can see the output there.

00:10:28.719 --> 00:10:30.880
It has an index at the front of it.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:31.880
The numbers are space-separated.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:34.239
There's no guarantee how long these could be.

00:10:34.239 --> 00:10:36.599
They could be integers, for example.

00:10:36.599 --> 00:10:38.479
So working with text is not great.

00:10:38.479 --> 00:10:43.119
And that's why WebR lets you work directly with R objects.

00:10:43.159 --> 00:10:48.159
So R objects are returned to the user as references and handled by something called a JavaScript

00:10:48.159 --> 00:10:49.159
proxy.

00:10:49.159 --> 00:10:54.159
Now, JavaScript proxies are really cool, because what they let you do is work with a certain

00:10:54.159 --> 00:10:57.679
object but then intercept fundamental operations.

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:03.840
So if you wanted to read a property of that object, or if you wanted to, say, invoke the

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:09.400
object as if it was a function, if you were doing that and you just had a number, that

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:13.000
would fail, because a number has no methods, a number cannot be invoked as a function.

00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:18.880
But proxies let you step in and say, OK, I'll do something else instead, whenever you try

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:20.400
and do these things.

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:26.640
So by storing a reference to an R object and then using the proxy to handle these things,

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:33.400
it means that you don't need to pass around giant pieces of memory full of numbers.

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:40.119
So here, for example, if you evaluate some R code to generate a vector, that R code is

00:11:40.119 --> 00:11:44.760
evaluated and then the result is returned back to the user, not as a vector, but as

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:45.760
a number.

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:51.960
And that number there, the SS number, which is short for S expression, it's a lispy thing,

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:54.840
it's old R stuff.

00:11:54.840 --> 00:12:01.280
That pointer, that number, uniquely identifies that object in R memory.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:04.960
So when you're working with that R object in JavaScript, JavaScript doesn't really need

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:08.840
to know what that is, it just needs to know this is an R object, and this is where it

00:12:08.840 --> 00:12:09.840
lives.

00:12:09.840 --> 00:12:11.479
It lives here in memory.

00:12:11.479 --> 00:12:15.679
And then when you do need the numbers, say you actually want to convert that number into

00:12:15.679 --> 00:12:22.760
JavaScript or you want to invoke that function, only then does WebR actually go and use RcApi

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:25.739
to do the hard work to actually get those numbers.

00:12:25.739 --> 00:12:33.520
So here you can see only after I actually ask WebR to convert to JavaScript, only then

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:36.520
that big long list of numbers is returned.

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:41.159
Now here there's only five numbers, but you can imagine if this was a million lines long

00:12:41.159 --> 00:12:45.320
or it had something like 10 million points, that would make a real difference because

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:50.260
otherwise you'd be passing this object around between JavaScript and R all of the time.

00:12:50.260 --> 00:12:58.359
So this is a really nice way to deal with handling R objects in WebR.

00:12:58.359 --> 00:13:02.440
One more thing I want to talk about with WebR is service workers.

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:08.479
So service workers is, again, a JavaScript feature that are very similar to web workers.

00:13:08.479 --> 00:13:13.559
But rather than acting as a proxy on a certain object, it acts as a network proxy.

00:13:13.559 --> 00:13:19.799
And what that means is that when you ask for a website in your browser, if you have a service

00:13:19.799 --> 00:13:25.479
worker loaded, that can step in and say, no, I don't want you to talk to Google.com, instead

00:13:25.479 --> 00:13:29.520
you will connect to Bing or something like that.

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:31.640
It doesn't even have to be another website.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:37.159
This could step in, stop the network traffic, compute something itself, and then return

00:13:37.159 --> 00:13:42.239
that as the result.

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:45.179
And that's how Shiny Live for Python already works.

00:13:45.179 --> 00:13:51.640
Whenever you have a Shiny Live session in your page, and a network connection is made

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:58.299
to what would normally be a Shiny server, a service worker steps in and redirects that

00:13:58.299 --> 00:14:04.219
traffic to a running PyEdit process inside a web worker.

00:14:04.219 --> 00:14:11.820
And the same thing works for R. But here, WebR is acting as the bridge.

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:16.340
So the service worker intercepts the network traffic, and then all those tricks with WebR,

00:14:16.340 --> 00:14:20.380
all of that magic of interacting with the environment, that can be used by the service

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:27.340
worker to send that traffic, instead of a Shiny server, into a web worker process.

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:33.219
And because the web worker process is running an R WebAssembly, loading packages like Shiny,

00:14:33.219 --> 00:14:38.780
it can do that computation and return the result without hitting the network at all.

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:43.739
And this is exactly how Shiny Live for R works.

00:14:43.739 --> 00:14:45.099
That's all I have to speak about today.

00:14:45.099 --> 00:14:46.780
So thank you very much for listening.

