00:15:12.099 --> 00:15:19.260
How do you navigate through browser security context restricted network connections in

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:22.380
WebR?

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:27.739
One thing I need to make clear is you cannot really work around browser security restrictions.

00:15:27.739 --> 00:15:32.059
Browsers are written to be very secure by default, and they're constantly updated.

00:15:32.059 --> 00:15:36.780
So even if we came up with some tricks to be able to load content across domain or something

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:40.859
like that, these tricks, they wouldn't be stable, and you'd be constantly fighting with

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:41.940
the browser.

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:45.260
I think that is the bad thing to do.

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:51.299
There are tricks you can use, but generally, the way to think about this is that when you

00:15:51.299 --> 00:15:59.700
interact with the network in a browser from inside a website, there is a way for the server

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:04.299
at the other end to tell the browser whether you're allowed to do that.

00:16:04.299 --> 00:16:07.700
This is called HTTP cause headers.

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:10.219
So really, we should be following those rules.

00:16:10.219 --> 00:16:14.739
And if a web server decides, yes, you're allowed to talk to us, they will let you know

00:16:14.739 --> 00:16:16.380
by setting these headers.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:21.500
And I think that is the correct way to think about this, is how do we make these HTTP headers

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:26.979
more common throughout the internet so that when it makes sense to do such connections,

00:16:26.979 --> 00:16:29.979
we are allowed to do so.

00:16:29.979 --> 00:16:30.979
Thank you.

00:16:30.979 --> 00:16:34.219
Someone else had a question about are there protections put in place to prevent users

00:16:34.219 --> 00:16:40.140
from running computationally expensive R code in WebR?

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:46.260
Not by WebR, but browsers are very clever, and in particular, Safari is very good at

00:16:46.260 --> 00:16:49.179
stopping things when they get a little out of hand.

00:16:49.179 --> 00:16:54.340
I have on a few occasions slipped up when programming, like all of us, and caused a

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:56.179
browser thread to crash.

00:16:56.179 --> 00:16:59.500
What Safari will do is it will just show a little bar at the top of the screen that says

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:02.299
this process has crashed, I've restarted it for you.

00:17:02.299 --> 00:17:07.780
Which sounds great until you realize you've lost an entire shiny live app, but anyway.

00:17:07.780 --> 00:17:10.579
So browsers will normally take care of themselves.

00:17:10.579 --> 00:17:16.739
One thing that WebR does not do, that I would like to do, is add limits such as computational

00:17:16.739 --> 00:17:21.219
time, so that after, say, ten seconds of computation, the process is interrupted.

00:17:21.219 --> 00:17:26.739
That would be really nice and useful, particularly for people running WebR inside Node, but that's

00:17:26.739 --> 00:17:27.739
not there yet.

00:17:27.739 --> 00:17:28.739
It's on the road map.

00:17:28.739 --> 00:17:31.719
We have time for maybe one or two more.

00:17:31.719 --> 00:17:37.160
Someone wants to know, is it possible to invoke R functions that have, in scare quotes, side

00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:38.160
effects?

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:43.000
I mean, try it!

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.439
I think so.

00:17:44.439 --> 00:17:46.000
It depends what you mean by side effects, I think.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.319
I think that person should come and talk to me.

00:17:49.319 --> 00:17:55.239
It's not something I've really tried heavily, but I will say that the way that shiny live

00:17:55.239 --> 00:18:00.800
for R is set up, this process of invoking functions, that happens directly in shiny

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:01.800
live.

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:07.560
We actually invoke the HTTP UV app directly to be able to return what that app would have

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:11.560
returned if it was running inside a web server.

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:17.160
So we do use it, but it's hard to say.

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:18.160
Last question.

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:24.599
Do you have a good idea of how performance compared between native R and WebR compares

00:18:24.599 --> 00:18:28.719
and how it varies between certain types of calculations?

00:18:28.719 --> 00:18:29.719
I don't.

00:18:29.719 --> 00:18:31.400
I think it's something I've tested heavily.

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:36.800
I will say that the literature, from what I've read, the basic idea that people talk

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:41.079
about when they talk about Wasm is about 80 per cent of native speed.

00:18:41.079 --> 00:18:42.439
I don't know how true that is.

00:18:42.439 --> 00:18:44.640
It's just what I've heard.

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:48.560
Even the fact that you can get to something like that is incredible to me, considering

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:53.640
the security benefits that you're getting by sandboxing your code and making sure it

00:18:53.640 --> 00:18:58.800
can't destroy your file system, or the fact that you can get such reproducible guarantees

00:18:58.800 --> 00:19:04.000
about the order of operations of numerical and floating point issues, for example.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.760
All of that good stuff that you get and you're still at over 50 per cent of native speed

00:19:08.760 --> 00:19:10.400
to me is incredible.

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:11.800
But I don't have exact numbers, no.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:12.800
Thank you.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:14.359
Can we have one more hand for George?

00:19:14.359 --> 00:19:15.359
Thank you.

00:19:15.359 --> 00:19:15.359


